<br>
<p>
    We started the project with a rasberry pi, because a rasberry pi cannot work with analog values we came across an error while trying to send data
    from the accelerometer to the pi. The accelerometer we had was an analog. The pi can only read digital values, as the GPIO pins are digital.
    To fix this issue we used an MCP 3008 that can convert the values inherited from the accelerometer and send it to the pi
    to display the  values and use them in the calculations.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    We came across so many issues trying to convert the data from analog to digital with the MCP that we scraped that idea and decided to use an arduino instead.
    The arduino can input and output analog values which makes it the better option over the rasberry pi for this project.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    The accelerometer works in meters per second(m/s²).The accelerometer can measure acceleration on three different axes(x,y and z axis).
    We need to calculate the average velocity between each rotation the lidar does. The reason we need to do this is to see how big each bump or crack is in the pipe.
    So we trying to calculate the distance traveled between each rotation.
    The calculations will be the following:<br>
<p>To calculate Distance:</p>
<br>
<ul class="steps">
    <li>Get acceleration from accelerometer</li>
    <li>Get time from the time it takes for one full revolution the lidar does, this will be a constant</li>
    <li>Final velocity = intial velocity+(acceleration*time)</li>
    <li>Distance = Final velocity * time</li>
</ul>
    </p>
<br>
<p>
    The accelerometer will not only be used for the calculation of distance, but also to see if the pipe has any bends, turns or if it changes its angle.
    We need this information so when we create a 3d image of the pipe, all bends, turns and slopes will be included so it does not look like the pipe is just one straight line.
</p>
